< Review>
The quality of this place depends on the person who you get to do your hair, truly. I think that pretty much goes for every salon. I have always gone here to get my hair cut because of the convenience of its location. Normally the quality is just good, and I just went back today for a hair trim and eyebrow touch-up, and they gave me excellent service. Basically, the people there (today) were very friendly and didn't cut any corners (pun intended) with doing their job. You can't really judge the entire salon based off of one time going there. That's one stylist in probably about 8-15 stylists. In the past, normally the service was about 3.5 to 4 stars, and today I'd definitely give it 5 stars. So that's my opinion. Take it or leave it.< /Review>

<rating>5</rating><Gmap_id>0x80dd35f50ce5bf35:0x9f044d35ff3c6594</Gmap_id>< Review>
Its sooo good.  My hubby introduced me to this little korean chicken place, right across kaiser on pch in harbor city.  Great find.  I have only had a few of the flavors but if anyone wants a great spicy, crispy fried in, not gooped on chicken wing (and drumsticks), order the hot and crispy.  Its plenty hot and im vietnamese so im saying its good enough for me.  I tried 3 other flavors but this is the one i go back to...worth it.</Review>

<rate>4<//rate><GmapID>0x80dd35f50ce5bf35:0x9f044d35ff3c6594<//GmapID><UserId.>105794409513593571420</UserId.><username>Reena Clions</username>< pictures>
None</pictures>
<Text>I fell in love with Kokio in Cerritos and got myself hyped up finding out there is one closer to me in Harbor City!!
Then my excitement only left me with disappointment :/

CHICKEN:
- Half & Half ($20.50)
- Honey Bee: THIS IS THEIR SPECIALTY! Honestly with so many KFC (Korean Fried Chicken) shops around, this is what sets themselves apart. However, the flavor fell incredibly short to the Cerritos location - less crispy, less juicy, not as sweet.
- Hot Crispy: Original crispy but (barely) hot. This was super crispy but maybe too much flour/breading? It took me a couple bites to actually bite into the chicken.

SERVICE:
- There was only one server, which makes sense because it's more of a to-go shop. We were the only dine-in customers but he did a real good job serving us while taking care of phone/to-go orders
- Not sure what was going on but we started to hear loud yelling inside the kitchen (restaurant is quite small and we were sitting directly facing the kitchen). Seemed like the manager/owner was also involved but the yelling continued with cursing as well... it was to the point I was distracted in our conversations. This was a very uncomfortable experience at a small restaurant...

TIPS:
- Parking in the shared plaza (quite small and sketchy)
- No alcoholic drinks... which is usually a staple to KFC
- Maybe sit at the far ends (TV/kitchen can be distracting) or just order to-go

I know Kokio is good... this location is still new and need some improvements. So so sad to say but I would probably visit other OC locations in the meanwhile.< /Text>< time>

<Review>I came here on a Sunday afternoon with the lady, after I was told that this place had some fairly good reviews despite being quite a new location in the heart of Buena Park.

It was quite empty on a Sunday afternoon, as we came in minutes after opening time, at 11:40.  The restaurant got very busy and packed after we were seated so good thing we placed our orders in early.  Initial service was fine--waiter Khang took our orders and offered some of his recommendations--we basically filled out the dim sum menu card.  To be honest, prices are much higher than average dim sum restaurants but then again, its cleanliness and bright atmosphere makes up for the price.

We ordered the following: 4 PCS of pork xiu mai, 4 PCS of jumbo har gao, steamed fish, spicy string beans, and a bowl of jasmine rice.

The pork xiu mai was just delicious--had a very mouth-watering taste and didn't feel oily or fatty at all. The aftertaste was just perfect, and the dipping sauce made it a great mixture.  The har gao was excellent--again, rich in flavour, and the size of the shrimp was humongous.  My personal favourite was the steamed fish--had great garlic flavoured sauce with chopped onions.  The aftertaste of the fish felt great--just tasty and mouth-watering--a definite must if you're a fish lover.  The spicy stringed beans were good, but in my opinion, was a tad bit overcooked.

I would come back again, but it's only if I feel like splurging on a nice luncheon on occasion only.  A regular dim sum lunch with these items totalling to $34 seems a bit steep in my opinion.

Overall grade: A-<//Review>< name>
Bobby Kompson<//name>
<Time>1575641065271<//Time>< Response>
None< /Response>

I was teetering between a 2 or 3 star rating so I'll let you decide with this review...

The food. It was good. I ordered the steak tacos. Steak was flavful, huicy, and tender. But it onlyocame with 2 street sized tacos? Usually there's at least 3 in combo meals and for the price I paid, I would expect 3 at the very least. It came with a side of two different styles of rice and beans.

<Review>This is a great facility in San Macros, conveniently located   in the middle of the san Diego county, in which help for all the teams to come and play  tournaments.

Parking is little tight here but they do have multiple entry points to the park, so you can plan accordingly. I would suggest to look at the Google map to see the various entry points so that you can street park and get into the park conveniently.

This park have 7 baseball fields and 3 patches for throw practices.  They do how multiple restaurant areas and booth for snacks and coffee.

If you have smaller kids there is a play area right in the center of the park and it's convenient for the families to drop that kids and watch the game.

The perk for parents, there are multiple micro breweries around this park so feel free to have a beer or 2 after the game.< /Review>< Pics>

< user_id>
110459430562921344871< /user_id>
<Name>Sunny Shin<//Name><date>1572823487065</date><rate>4< /rate>< text>
Beautiful spacious and private campgrounds. We had a campsite next to the creek and it was beautiful to see and listen to.

Cons: The incessant number of bugs during the day- flies, gnats, wasps- you name it.
People dont pick up after themselves or dogs. We had an excess of flies due to the overwhelming number of poop puddles left throughout just our campsite alone- ppl left trash, human waste, vomit puddles.
Other than that- the campgrounds are beautiful with the natural vegitation mix of what seem to be some sort of large succulent with an abundance of beautiful trees and shrubs. The creek or stream is a good size- its not just a tiny trickle- you can hear the running stream while you sleep. At night, we camped during a no fire period so no campfires or outdoor propane gas stove fires. We sat in the darkness and took in the stars with the sound of the creek below us.
Campsite comes with a picnic table, a small fire pit ring and bbq grill. We camped with five little dogs-  crowds usually give me anxiety for fear of them barking and disturbing the peace but the space between each campsite was ample and private enough to put my mind at ease.
Highly recommend if sites are clean.</text>

None</Pics>
<Resp>None<//Resp><GmapID>0x80c31f57ce44adef:0xe418f7e1535c83d6<//GmapID></record></dataset><record>
<user>117987446456100157921< /user>< user_name>
Jenny Yu</user_name>
<Date>1468050437983<//Date>< rating>
5</rating>
<Text>This place is such a little gem in the San Gabriel Mountains! As some of the previous reviews mentioned, the brook runs through most of the camps, which is super nice.  My bf and I had a great time playing in it; the downside was that a lot of other campers kept coming over. It was also a great place to watch stars at night- so peaceful and serene.  Little critters paid us several visits at night; their rustling kept us on the edge, since we were aware of a bear attack in those mountains a few weeks back.

It's important to know that not all campsites are the same size. I think our site was one of the bigger ones; there were others where the parking spots were bigger than the site itself. Most of our neighbors seem to pack up around 10 or 11 AM, although as we can attest, coming early doesn't mean getting the best spot  [my bf and I got the last available spot]. Check out is 2pm.

Lastly, some of the reviews said there is lot of fire wood. We found a lot of tinder, but not enough big logs to sustain ourselves for the night, so we drove up to Crystal Lake [approx. 8 miles north] for some. The store aka the cafe sells them by the wheelbarrow for $20. Even though it seems a lot, it was just enough for the evening  [we slept at midnight, so the fire burned for 6hrs]. We also used it to cook, since the grill over the fire pit kinda disappeared.<//Text>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>

< review>
Great campground, clean bathrooms, friendly host. Campsites are clean, there are fire rings on every site, and bbqs on every site. Fills up quickly on weekends, pretty quiet week days. Fees$12 nightly. Lots of hiking trails, and a creek . There are water stickers throughout campground and it is drinkable water.< /review>

<rate>5</rate>< date>
1405370265974</date>
<user_name>Brenda Ho<//user_name><Response>None< /Response><pics>None< /pics><Text>We had a great time at Coldbrook Campground. It was packed during the weekend, so get there early. Everyone cleared out on Sunday afternoon (check out time is 2pm), so that was very nice! The camp host Ron was very friendly and helpful.

During our stay there was a juvenile bear who had been poking around the area for the past few weeks. Unfortunately the campers next to us were very very irresponsible and left their food out all day. The bear walked into their camp and stole some food, despite them banging pots and pans and shouting. And since they didn't clean up their food right away after that, the bear came back again a few minutes later. They were very disrespectful for not putting everything away, which puts people and especially the bear in danger. The bear struck the same camp again around dinner time, but was chased off with a bean bag gun. Please put all your food and coolers in your car trunk and don't be stupid. It was very frustrating seeing this happen and the family not really caring. They also left garbage everywhere when they left.

Campsites are great, not very secluded from each other, so it was a little annoying during the busy weekend. There are spigots everywhere for drinking water, and the creek was great to cool off in. There are vault bathrooms. Crystal Lake is a 2 mile drive up the mountain if you want to do some fishing and hiking. There is also a small restaurant and general store.< /Text><user_id>113221660343950475993</user_id>< Gmap_id>

<rate>4</rate>< Text>
I got an engine oil change with Synthetic Oil which I feel lasts longer and performs better than petroleum oil. The service took a lot longer to get done than I like to wait and there was only one car being worked on ahead of mine. They did top off all fluids including the windshield washer fluid. However, when I went to get gas and restarted my car it sputtered and died right away. I then started it again, revved the engine a bit, and it was ok thereafter. I looked under the hood and the washer fluid cap was gone. I'm guessing they didn't tighten it up well and it flew off in between Jiffy Lube and the gas station. $6.45 on Amazon and I'm back in business with that cap. More of an annoyance and time-suck than anything. I of course took my car back to Jiffy Lube and they were very professional about reinspecting the engine. They offered to replace the cap and promised to get back to me with a small refund to cover the cost. That hasn't happened yet. We'll see if they do contact me.
All in all, the oil change was good, people there were very professional, and I will likely go back next time oil change is due.<//Text>

< Text>

Within a two month timeframe he was in the emergency room at Loma Linda 3 different times. If your family member cannot speak for themselves DO NOT send them here. I have educated myself on patients rights and learned how to be an excellent advocate for my son.< /Text>

< review>
UPDATE: Funny how a store can leave such a bad taste in a customers mouth after being a favorite. This went from one of my favorite locations, to now one of my least favorite. My lady and I wanted to buy a little shelf that was out on the floor with nothing on it. It was perfect dimensions for what I needed it for, and in this situation it was urgent. I asked if we can get a price check on it, and they told me it was a "display" shelf and that it's not for sale. Are you kidding me? There were so many other shelves that they could use for "display". All the other shelves didn't have enough depth for what I needed it for, but this one did. Right next to this shelf is also a huge wire shelf that was half empty and being used for display. As a recurring customer, I felt appalled by this. This seemingly stupid shelf that served little to no purpose to them wouldn't be sold when I would have gladly bought for more than its obviously worth because of my urgent situation. Lame, and left a bad taste in my mouth.

TLDR; They wouldn't sell me a small wooden shelf that had nothing on it because it was a "display". My situation was urgent, the shelf was perfect for me, and they had tons of other shelves to use for "display".

ORIGINAL: One if my favorite goodwills to shop at. Nice location with a variety of goods. Naturally, most of the stuff will be considered junk goods here. However, a few times I have found unique goods for very cheap. I'd say check it out if you have the chance and you're in the area.<//review>

<user_id>115915709081006443103<//user_id><name>Jim Redmond</name><Resp>None</Resp>< text>
I've been to many different types of show at the Castro Theater, and it's always a great time. The concession stand is somewhat basic compared to other theaters, but there are plenty of good bars and restaurants nearby.

Come a bit early, and there's often a mini-concert on the organ. (The closing number on the night I took the pic was the Liberty Bell March - very appropriate for a Monty Python double feature.) Sing-alongs and Peaches Christ shows are also lots of fun.< /text>

<Review>Fun comfy old theater. Definitely not state of the art sound or projection, but come here for a cultural experience, and vintage style.  If you are lucky the classic pipe organ will be playing and other live elements that make this place one of a kind.< /Review><time>1582182673832</time></record>
</dataset><record>
< Text>
Just saw the premier of The Irishman here. As a lifelong movie fan, this is among my favorite movie theaters I've ever been to. It has that awesome retro feel that you get at small town movie theaters, but the difference is that this one is located right in The Castro, one of the most fun and vibrant neighborhoods of the city, and that its capacity is absolutely massive - it can seat a whopping 1,400 people! There is excellent sound quality, the screen is very big, and the seats are reasonably comfortable. The interior design is beautiful.

Tips: come here early, especially if you're coming to a movie's opening night, as there are no assigned seats and the line for concession and even the bathrooms can get ridiculously long before a sold-out screening. You can (and should) buy tickets online to make sure you get in. And finally, unlike most AMC theaters, the movies here start almost exactly on time - maybe 5-10 minutes after the scheduled start time. So aim to be here 15-30 minutes early if you want to get snacks / use the bathroom / secure the best seats in the house.< /Text>
<userid>112623089326463590809< /userid><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMLU4jhKc6vgznmIY-zG_PhK4g9_9TvW6txxCEk=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP9tsKMCaensEW-3wMyn_KpHDM9PRfJO74SF7ot=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNt5ChKYaN8HN8FMhS1CW3q4vb0I7KhojYkxqY0=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO4lYDQwquku0g26dIjeKkGI16zTl4ehMHqTAHe=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>< Name>

< text>
This is one of the great theaters in the world.

A comfortable, and amazing experience always. Every show is not merely "seeing a movie" -- it's an event. Most films are double features and there's always something special about the show. Go on their website, and go see something that looks interesting to you. Tons of great movies, and it changes every weekend. Incredible theater!< /text>

<Date>1551757196939< /Date>< rating>

< Gmap_id>
0x808f7e1b4ff86179:0x14fad42ba6399425</Gmap_id>
<Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMz9jdQeoW6g0Z1airiJQMZ-dc1SfUmqFIFt3Wm=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><user_name>Dan Brook</user_name><UserId.>116838550636744514823</UserId.>< Text>
The Castro is a beautiful and historic theater on Castro Street, near Market, in the heart of the Castro, the famous gay neighborhood. The 1400-seat theater has a live organist, a beautiful interior, and is chock full of history. It's great to see old kitschy movies there or go for a film festival or special screening. The Castro Theatre is a treasure!

[Update March 2019]
I love the Castro Theatre and have been here many times over the years.

Last night, I went with friends to the Bohemian Rhapsody Sing-a-Long, which was one of the most fun nights I've had in years. Of course I had already seen the movie, which you should anyway but it makes this kind of event even better, and then seeing it this way was a special treat.

With a $16 admission, you get a goodie bag filled with a paper gold crown, which most people wore, a glow stick, a popper thing, and a little bottle for blowing bubbles. The theatre was completely packed with a diverse crowd ready for fun.

The Castro Theatre is beautiful, they have a live organist, arranged a little costume show off, and seem to care about their patrons enjoying themselves.

We sang, we sighed, we whooped, we applauded and we hissed, we laughed and we cried, and we were all in it together. Like Queen says about Queen, we were a family, at least for a couple hours. And it was magical.

I shall return.</Text>
</record></dataset><record>
< text>
We did the Bohemian Rhapsody sing-along here. Everybody was given a bag of party goodies, including glow lights. We sat in the balcony of the jam packed theater. The preshow, with Freddie Mercury impersonator contest & performance, put everyone in a festive mood.

But, the experience I'll relish forever was during the sing-along the entire audience would wave their glow lights, creating a rich tapestry of color & light. It's rare that you have a performance that engages an audience's senses the way this movie has. When it was over everyone felt exhilarated, as if they had witness something truly special.

I love this theater, I love this movie, and I loved the audience.< /text>

Huw Thomas</Name>
<time>1546240779397< /time>< rating>
5< /rating>
< Review>
Watched 2001: A Space Odyssey here this evening and can confidently say that this is my favorite cinema anywhere. It was built in the 1920s and is incredibly beautiful inside. The prices are very reasonable, the seats comfortable and the hardware very good though not what you would expect from a newer cinema. If you want a truly 'authentic' experience watching some of the best movies humanity has even made, though, this is the place!<//Review>

<user_id>103208015192776997537< /user_id>< user_name>
Mercedes Lamperti< /user_name>
<time>1576429456736<//time>< rate>
5<//rate>
< text>
The Castro Theatre is a popular San Francisco movie palace which became San Francisco Historic Landmark #100 in September 1976.[2] Located at 429 Castro Street, in the Castro district, it was built in 1922 with a California Churrigueresque fa√ßade that pays homage‚Äîin its great arched central window surmounted by a scrolling pediment framing a niche‚Äîto the recently rebuilt basilica of Mission Dolores nearby. Its designer, Timothy L. Pflueger, also designed Oakland's Paramount Theater and other movie theaters in California in that period. The theater has over 1,400 seats (approx 800 downstairs and 600 in the balcony).[3][4] The theater's ceiling is the last known leatherette ceiling in the United States and possibly the world.[citation needed] Another leatherette ceiling was demolished just a few years ago.[where?] To make the ceiling look as though it is leather requires a special technique regarded as lost today.[by whom?]< /text>

Whether a campy live drag show from Peaches Christ, a camp classic like Mommie Dearest, or the Film Noir Festival, or a Sing-Along you will have the time of your life in this 1929 movie palace. <Text>The Castro Theatre is probably the most historic theatre in the Bay Area. Whether you're here for a film festival, an old movie screening, a sing-a-long, a comedy performance or a drag show, you're bound to have a blast! The interior design is magnificent. <date>1576429456736< /date>< rate>
5<//rate>
< Review>
The Castro Theatre is a popular San Francisco movie palace which became San Francisco Historic Landmark #100 in September 1976.[2] Located at 429 Castro Street, in the Castro district, it was built in 1922 with a California Churrigueresque fa√ßade that pays homage‚Äîin its great arched central window surmounted by a scrolling pediment framing a niche‚Äîto the recently rebuilt basilica of Mission Dolores nearby. Its designer, Timothy L. Pflueger, also designed Oakland's Paramount Theater and other movie theaters in California in that period. The theater has over 1,400 seats (approx 800 downstairs and 600 in the balcony).[3][4] The theater's ceiling is the last known leatherette ceiling in the United States and possibly the world.[citation needed] Another leatherette ceiling was demolished just a few years ago.[where?] To make the ceiling look as though it is leather requires a special technique regarded as lost today.[by whom?]< /Review>

< Review>
A holiday tradition now for my CA family. What can be more fun and camp but to dress up as characters, get a goodie bag of props, and have fun along with kids of all ages? Young and people with some mileage. This year we participated in the Sing Along Sound of Music. Last year it was Beauty and the Beast. There are lots of different movies at the Castro Theater in the midst of a colorful area of SF.  And they publish a monthly schedule. This Art Deco Palace Theater is fully restored, along with the theater organ which is played before the movie. Look hard and you will see a lotus, Buddhas, and other exotic things to transport you to another time and place. Truly a taste of the magic of Hollywood.</Review>

< Rate>
3<//Rate>
<review>The six vertical letters attached to the facade of the theater are probably the brightest part of the building. I have to say I am a bit disappointed by its dark interior that really can use some good lighting. The seats are comfortable but the decorations look very dull. I can tell there used to be glory but they faded away and desperately needs some restoration.

Even so, I appreciate what the theater does for the community. We went for a Saturday three features marathon starting from 5 pm until almost midnight. You can have your hand stamped and go out eat and come back later during the shows. The projection on the screen is not super sized but it's crispy clear. The echo of audio is little bit distracting, but I bet that adds flavor to live performance and concerts. Even this place is not brand new, but facility is maintained and functioning well.

The best of if is that it does not show 40-minutes long commercials in other for profit cinemas. You go in, enjoy the live organ performance to soothe your mind, then lights dim and movie starts.

I bet there are lot of memories and stories heard and seen by the high ceiling. I hope people will continue to support the iconic monument that is part of the history.</review>< username>
Phil Ye<//username>

<pictures>None< /pictures><Text>I've been wanting to go see a movie at The Castro Theatre for a very long time.  I finally got to go when they were showing Vertigo.

It's a beautiful venue, and I thought it was so cool that there was an organ player before the movie.

And for such a historic theatre, and for being in a popular neighborhood, the ticket prices are reasonable.  I didn't buy anything at the concession stand, but my roommates did and they said it was expensive.  Better to eat beforehand.

<UserId.>104273864834150964663< /UserId.>< username>
Scott Johnson<//username>
< time>
1507225161631< /time>
<rate>1</rate>< review>
Watched Lawrence of Arabia here in 70mm film to remind myself how a proper film presentation can be. Left very disappointed. Audio quality was terrible: lots of echo in the room; music was shrill and harsh. Picture quality was poor: extreme hot spotting; visible seams and distortions in the screen material; extreme flicker; and a worn-out projector that resulted in repeated incidents of violent vertical shaking of the picture for several seconds at a time. The film even stopped at one reel change and the audience sat there in the dark for several minutes while they fixed it.

At the intermission, there was a power outage and the second half was not shown. The theater offered rain checks, but I didn't bother. I watched the second half at home with much better picture and sound quality. Even my popcorn is better.

The place is a grand old palace. The sing-alongs are fun, and there‚Äôs always a nice crowd, but don‚Äôt go for the presentation quality.<//review>

<userid>106849278306281839192< /userid><user_name>Rachel Levine Photography< /user_name><Date>1550244903998<//Date>< rating>
5</rating>
< review>
Castro Theater is a gift to everyone who visits it. From the moment you walk in and smell the organic popcorn with real butter to taking your seats and listening to the live organ player you are transported to a vintage happy place.
The organ comes up out of the floor like Posiden rising up from a storm sea! It‚Äôs huge and the music is just the coolest thing. Everyone applauds loudly when the musician is done playing and then it goes back down under the floor and the movie starts. The whole room with an upper balcony is beautifully restored. A historic landmark.

They have film festivals, like Frameline and the Jewish Film Festival every year, and classic movies, singalongs and current films. It‚Äôs a great venue on all fronts.</review>

< text>
A gorgeous old theatre with comfortable seats.  I've seen two shows here - both from the main floor.  I had no difficulty seeing the stage and performers without getting blocked by people in the row ahead of me.  There was enough leg room to stretch out a little also.

There's popcorn and a few snacks but no alcohol served at the theatre bar.</text>

<Rate>4</Rate>< Text>
An old theater located just off of Castro and Market. This place has its charm and is used to feature any and all types of events. I went there particularly to see a "Singalong" of the movie Grease. Singalongs are where the movie is shown and the whole audience sings along when the movie characters starts singing, and lyrics are shown at the bottom of the screen (it was a fun thing to do with friends, which I would not mind doing again).</Text>

< review>
The films shown here range from the ridiculous "sing-alongs" (Little Mermaid,  Frozen) once a month to true classics noone should miss (Doctor Zhivago, Vertigo). The interior and organ solo are worth the price of a ticket alone. If you want to know what it was like to see a movie in the Golden Age of Hollywood this is the place to go.< /review>

<username>Me Go<//username>< user_id>
113514808075531939419<//user_id>
<gmapID>0x808f7e1b4ff86179:0x14fad42ba6399425<//gmapID><date>1551412432812<//date>< Text>
This is one of many beautiful theatres around San Francisco.  It was built in 1922 featuring a Spanish Colonial Baroque style facade.  Interior is very plush and ornate, capped off with an over the top extravagant Art Deco Period chanellier.  The original 1920's Werlitzer organ is still used on occassion.< /Text>

< UserId.>
103177631366246678233</UserId.>
<review>I usually come here for the Noir City film festival. I dress up and haul all the way out to the City to watch other people's bad luck in black and white, and it's glorious. Most people dress up to go to this event, there's specialty cocktails at intermission along with concessions downstairs (they have It's Its!), and the second story has vendors relating to the event, like pulp fiction, makeup, and Noir City merchandise.

The theater itself is BEAUTIFUL inside - vaulted ceiling with gilded carvings, a second story balcony, velvet stadium seating, and a stage in front of the single screen. They even have an organ! It's a gorgeous example of an old time movie theater, and it feels like the kind of place to dress up for, even if it's not Noir City time. I love it. This would be a great place to bring a date, especially because of the fabulous food and drinks around here for nibbles before or after. Cannot recommend enough!< /review><date>1549009335455< /date><Resp>None<//Resp>< Rate>
5< /Rate>

< Review>
The Castro Theater is a downright delicious time! You just feel excited when you walk in. They show such gem movies, so definitely check out their website for a list of what they will be playing during the month.Someone usually plays the organ before the film which is such a classic touch. The old school theater seats make trying to hold a dates hand or cuddle rather difficult, so just sit back and revel in your feature film! Easy to get to from Muni, but parking around there can take some serious work and eagle eyes.<//Review>

< user_name>
gemma soyls<//user_name>
< Time>
1533196432417</Time>
<rate>4< /rate>< text>
What a grand theatre with a live organist who plays music on the Whirlitzer before each show. Double features make the $13 ticket price less  costly. Too bad the box office doesn't offer a student discount.

The seats aren't the most comfortable, yet the grandeur of yesteryear makes one forget about the discomfort. If one is phyically disabled, the restrooms are downstairs and there's no elevator to get there.

The Jewish film festival makes me keep coming back.<//text>

< Review>
Such an ideal community space! The Castro theatre hosts Disney singalongs, indie films, film festivals, drag shows, etc.

There's always something going on there, and it's conveniently right outside MUNI. Before your show, it's easy to grab a bite in the Mission too.

Organ playing before shows is always a nice touch.< /Review>

<Text>A San Francisco gem. I love coming here for classic movies.<//Text><Pictures>None</Pictures><Response>None<//Response><Gmap_id>0x808f7e1b4ff86179:0x14fad42ba6399425</Gmap_id></record>
</dataset><record>
<user_id>112805788702670078783<//user_id><Name>Ferrin< /Name><date>1379468813076< /date><rate>5< /rate>< review>
Let's be real: The Castro theatre is heaven on Earth. It's a magical, gaudy, single-screen venue that continues to weather economic storms. Before special events, you'll delight at the organist who plays you into the films. Numerous double or triple bills give you insane bang for your buck.

There is likely no one reading this who hasn't been to the Castro Theatre. But if you haven't, GO. It doesn't matter what's playing! GO. If you're visiting town, and you don't take a couple hours to check out a program at the Castro, you haven't seen one of San Francisco's true landmarks.</review>

<rate>5<//rate>< Text>
Great classic theater. I only really come for the sing a longs. They do play other movies here both new and old and have a monthly schedule posted on their website. Anyone reading this should totally go to one of their sing a longs. You can dress in costume based on the movie theme and they really work hard on trying to make these things as interactive as possible. At the very least come for a sing a long you won't regret it or not the choice is yours...if you're boring. Jk. But not lol. They also serve the typical movie food: popcorn, candy, soda with a side of nutritional yeast (taste like cheese, smells like wet dog, totally nutritional though, did I mention the cheese part?) Anyway tell them Andrew sent you and get an akward look lol.</Text>

< Rate>
4<//Rate>
<text>The wonderful retro look and feel adds deeply when you get to attend the Noir Film Festival, and certainly a lot of nostalgia since the Frameline camps mostly out of this most iconic and accommodating family owned space.  The family does take care of the space which is costly, and though evident it's hard to keep up, they manage to do so, albeit a bit behind but not unsafe as this is a popular screening space for the many sing-alongs little girls have memorized by heart, big girls who tend to the little girl inside, and all the Moms & Dad's who love to spend the afternoon w/their little and their hundreds of little friend throughout the year.  They have real butter for their popcorn, too.  And finally for me, it's only a few blocks away and while rarely do they get first runs, they sometimes get them bearing the tailend run in the premium mall boxes.  Sometimes there's a double feature.  If you haven't been it's a great option awaiting your special screening of an old favorite on the large screen.üòÜ< /text>< pics>
None< /pics>

< Review>
The wonderful retro look and feel adds deeply when you get to attend the Noir Film Festival, and certainly a lot of nostalgia since the Frameline camps mostly out of this most iconic and accommodating family owned space.  The family does take care of the space which is costly, and though evident it's hard to keep up, they manage to do so, albeit a bit behind but not unsafe as this is a popular screening space for the many sing-alongs little girls have memorized by heart, big girls who tend to the little girl inside, and all the Moms & Dad's who love to spend the afternoon w/their little and their hundreds of little friend throughout the year.  They have real butter for their popcorn, too.  And finally for me, it's only a few blocks away and while rarely do they get first runs, they sometimes get them bearing the tailend run in the premium mall boxes.  Sometimes there's a double feature.  If you haven't been it's a great option awaiting your special screening of an old favorite on the large screen.üòÜ</Review>

<user_id>114163658858039149063</user_id>< name>
Marie T Fisher</name>
< Date>
1386284450449</Date>
< rate>
5<//rate>
< text>
I love the Castro Theatre. I've seen mainstream movies, choruses, independant film screenings, participated in sing-alongs, and everything in between here. Their calendar is varied and always changing. Many of the events can be found on Goldstar for half price, but the full price tickets are usually pretty reasonable as well. Be patient and purchase tickets to popular showing in advance as the lines can get long (though they move fast). Inside, the historic theatre is gorgeous. The lobby isn't much to see but the interior is very old timey and you will be amazed by that organ.</text>
